{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_iotite_ver01/data/sn84020064/00542866421/1930090401/0001.xml":{"full_text":"Weather\nARIZONA\u2014MostIy fair Thursday\nand Friday; little chance in temp\nerature.\nDOUGLAS\u2014The maximum temper\nature recorded in Douglas yester\nday was 91 degrees and the mini\nmum was 65.\nVOL. XXVIII.\n30 INDICTED IN ALLEGED ARIZONA FRAUD\n1 1 1 _\nFoul Play is Feared in Disappearance of Gotham Judge\n'Y rigoy en Refuses to Resign as President of Argentine\nMillions Are\nObtained In\nPromotions\nOperators of Romola,\nInc\u201e Heki Under $7,500\nBond On Mail Charge\nUse Of Mails In Scheme\nTo Defraud Is Charged\n26 Counts Included in In\ndictments Concerning\nMaricopa County Land\nLOS ANGELES, Sept. 3 (A\u2019j-\nRunrhlings of a gigantic mail fraud\nin which millions of dollars were\nalleged to have been secured from\ninvestors in all sections of the coun\ntry, were heard today when the\nfederal grand jury returned an in-\nVdictment involving 30 individuals in\nrne operations of Romola, Inc., a\nCalifornia and Arizona land de\nvelopment project.\nThe indietment, based on evt-\nIMence gathered by postoffice in\nrpectators after months of investiga\ntion of tha affauns of the company,\nincluded one cchnt of conspiracy\nand accused Ute defendants of using\nthe mgils in a scheme to defraud\nin connection wita the sale of\ngrapeauit lands in Shin-\nty, Arizona, and Riverside county,\nCal. Twenty six Bounties are em\ntTuccd in the indictment, predicated\n<Uontinued on Page Eight*\nReceiver Named\nFor Cady Lumber\nFirm At McNary\nSays Business Depression\nHas Left Company Un\nabte to\u2019Meet Obligations\n.TUCSON, Sept. 3 (47\u2014Arth J.\nMcQuatters, of McNary, Aris., was\nappointed auxiliary receiver of the\nCady Lumber corporation, largest\nproducer of lumber in the south\nwest, with headquarters at McNary,\nin federal court here today. He\ngave bond for $50,000.\nE. K. Bronson, of New Haven,\nConn., filed a petition for appoint\nment of the receiver, tin his peti\ntion Bronson alleges the Cady Lum\nber corporation is indebeted to him\nin the sum of $29,620.21.\nJames J. McNary, president of\nthe corporation, described the action\nas a \u201cfriendly\u201d suit.\nFixed assets of the corporation\nare said by Bronson to be $4,134,-\n756.80. \u201cQuick assets,\" however, he\ncharges are but $787,000. Business\ndepression and losses during the last\nfew months, Bronson alleges have\ncaused the corporation to become\nMhble to meet its obligations.\ncaused\nd^ble\nBEKNAL INSTALLED.\nMEXIC ALL Lower California\nMex., Sept. (47\u2014General Arturo\nBernal became governor today of\nthe northern district of Lower Cal\nifornia, succeeding Jose Maria\nTapia, who will return to Mexico\nCity to receive another federal ap\npointment.\nKnowing Death Was Closing in on Him,\n^ndree Wrapped Note Books in Shirt\nthen Lay on Them to Preserve Them\nU.S. War Debt Hat\nBeen Reduced Oner\nOne-Third Since 1919\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 3\nAmerica's gigantic war debt of\n126.596.701,000 has been reducsd by\nmore than one-third in 11 years\nsince the debt reached its peak\non August 31, 1919.\nThe treasury statement today\nshowed the public debt on August\n31 this year to total $16,187,636,000.\nThis was a slight increase over a\nmonth ago, but this situation re\nsulted from delay in applying the\nsinking fund to the retirement, it\nwas said, and is only temporary.\nDAILY\noou iilas V tlisp at ch\nGlowing Tribute Is\nGiven Frenchmen\nFor Ocean Flight\nFrenchmen\nMay Garner\n2 Million\nHuge Sum Expected to\nGo to Coste and Mate\nfor Flight\nFrance Giving Heroes\nOf Air Military Awards\nGigantic Welcome Planned\nUpon Return of Idols\nto Native Soil\nPARIS, Sept. 3 (47\u2014Paris return\ned to normal tonight after cheering\nitself hoarse lor 24 hours over the\ngreat trans-Atlantic flight to New\nxoxk us DicadOvnuf a^astc and\nMaurice Bellon to.\nOfficial honors and promotions are\nshowering in their direction. Coste\nwill be promoted to commander of\nthe legion of honor, one of the\nlegion\u2019s highest ranks, and it is ex\npected Bellonte will be mad? an\nofficer.\nBeilcnte's rank as a chevalier of\nthe legion dates only from a year\nor so ago, but in honor of his ex\nceptional achievement rules may be\nwaived.\nMay Reap Two Million\nBoth aviators also will move up\non the military reserve list. Coste,\nnow a captain, will become a major\nand Bellonte, a non-commissioned\nofficer, will advance to a second\nlieutenancy.\nAs to the financial rewards of\ntheir flight, they run into the mil\nlions of francs. The newspaper Le\nMatin said judging that from the\nstatements by Coste to his friends\nbefore he left, the sum of $2,000,000\nmight accrue to him under his con\ntracts and prizes.\nBut the Paris of the people, as\ndistinct from official Paris, is wait\ning for its two heroes to come for\nits own special accolade.\nCoste and Bellonte will receive\nthe welcome reserved by France for\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nI Germans, Frenchmen\nAnd Lindbergh All\nAt \u201cFamily Party\u201d!\nNEW YORK, Sept. 3. (47\u2014A quiet\nlittle \u201cfamily party\u201d was turned by\nflying men of three nations tonight\ninto what Mayor James J. Walker\nannounced was the greatest step to\nward peace of which he had ever\nheard.\nTurning their backs squarely upon\nthe old animosities of days when\nwar ruled the world and made them\nenemies. French and German fliers\nwho recently accomplished the\n'Continued on Page Eight)\n(Copyright, 1930, and All Rights Re\nserved in North and South Amer\nica and in Japan, by The Associ\nated Press.)\nTROMSOE, Norway,, Sept. 3. W\u2014\nFurther interesting discoveries, one\nof which was most sensational in its\nnature, were made today by Swedish\nand Norwegian experts examining\nthe relics of the Arctic expedition\nof Salomon August Andree brought\nto this port by Dr. Gunnar Horn and\nhis exploration party.\n\nTwr Notebooks Found\nThis most important new find,\ni overlooked until government scien\ntists began their investigation of the\nremains of the famous polar aerial\nargosy of 1897, and one which may)\n(Continued on Page Eight) J\nBellonte Stricken With\nStage Fright Ad\ndressing Huge Crowds\nOff For Dallas Today\nIn Quest Of $25,000\nQuestion Mark to Be\nFlown Back to France\nBy Paul Codos\nNEW YORK, Sept. 3 (47\u2014Two\nlittle men of modest manner were\nhailed by all New York today as\nthe latest giants of aviation.\nAt a luncheon in their honor, on\na ride around the harbor, in a\nparade through the streets, and at\ncity hall, Dieudonne Coste and\nMaurice Bellonte were given tu\nmultucus greeting that might hav\u00bb\nturned any head.\nThey smiled. They waved. They\nsaid they were having a grand\ntime. But quite evidently they re\nmained from their own viewpoint\njust a couple fe3ows who had\ntackled a tough job and had the\ngood fortune to succeed.\n\nWalker Addresses Pilots.\nPerhaps the most impressive of\nthe day\u2019s ceremonies was the of\nficial welcome at city hall, for\nthere they were reminded their\nflight, the first ever to be made\nnon-stop from Paris to New York,\ncompensated\u2014insofar as was pos\nsible\u2014for the loss of Charles Nun\ngesser and Francois Coll, the first\nto make the attempt.\n\u201cYou may be especially proud,\u201d\nMayor Walker told the fliers at\non Pave Eiuni.\nBig Reception For\nAviators Planned\nAt Dallas Landing\nCoste and Question Mark\nOn Texas Jump to Win\n$25,000 Offer.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 3 (47\u2014Capt.\nDieudonne Coste and Maurice\nBellonte announced through their\nmanager tonight they will take off\nat 5 a. m. (E.S.T.) tomorrow on\ntheir non-stop flight to Dallas,\nTexas, instead of at 8 a. m. (E.S.T.)\nas previously announced. They\nsaid the plane was in excellent\ncondition.\nDALLAS, Texas, Sept. 3 (47\u2014Ex\ncitement was high in Dallas to\nnight as preparations were rushed\nfor a real Texas welcome to Capt.\nDieudonne Coste and Maurice\nBellonte, aerial conquerors of the\nAtlantic, who are expected to land\nhere tomorrow evening to collect\na $25,000 prize.\nThe purse, offered by Col. Wil\nliam Easterwood, Jr., Dallas avia\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nEasterwood Happy\nOver Coste Jaunt\nFrom Paris To N. Y. i\nDUBLIN. Sept. 3 W\u2014 Col. W. E.\nEasterwood of Dallas, Texas, who\noffered $25,000 for a trans-Atlantic\nflight ending at Dallas, declared\ntonight that he was the \u201cmost sat\nisfied man in the world\u2019\u2019 at the\nsuccess of Capt. Dieudonne Coste\u2019s\nvoyage.\n\u201cThis has been the happiest day\nof my life and I am glad it was\nspent in Dublin,\u201d he said. \"This\nflight is one of the biggest things\nin aviation the world has yet seen.\u201d\nDOUGLAS. ARIZONA THURSDAY MORNING. SEPTEMBER I, 1930.\nHad $3,500\nOn Last Day\nHe Was Seen\nMystery Surrounding\nMissing Supreme Court\nJustice Deepens\ni\nJoseph F, Crater Last\nSeen At Brokerage Booth\nA \u201cMr. Crater\u201d Tells Post\nI Judge Is Not Missing,\nReport Says.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 3 (Ai\u2014Mys\ntery concerning the whereabouts\nof Supreme Court Justice Joseph\nI F. Crater, reported missing since\nAugust 6, deepened today. While\nthe New York Evening Post was\ninformed by telephone from the\njustice\u2019s summer home at Belgrade\nLake, M., that he is not missing,\nit was stated at the office of Uni\nted. States Senator Robert R. Wag\nner, the justice\u2019s former law asso\nciate. that Mrs. Crater had been\nthere several times to confer about\n(Continued on Page Elgin.'\nHints o\u00a3 Bribery\n\nFeature Close Of\nCampaign Hearing\nSenate Funds Committee\nAdjourns Until Middle\nof Month.\nCHICAGO, Sept. 3. <47\u2014The sen\nate campaign funds commitee which\nlor two days has been taking testi\nmony concerning congresswoman\nRuth Hanna McCormicK\u2019s invest\ngaticn into its activities, adjourned\nlate today until September 15.\nSenator Gerald P. Nye, of North\nDakota, chairman of the committee.\nand Senator Porter Hale, of Ver\nmont, who has been sitting with\nhim, immediately went into confer\nence.\n\u201cI am confident that September\n15 we shall have all the members\nof the committee to continue the\ninvestigation of this angle of the\ncommittee\u2019s business,\u201d Senator Nye l\nsaid. \u201cWe shall first take up other\nevidence of this spying, and then 1\ncontinue with the campaign funds I\ninvestigation.\n\nBash Fails to Appear\n\u201cI don't suppose the public gen\nerally secs the relation between this 1\nangle and the campaign of any\npolitical candidate, but we shall\nbide our time and let that phase\ntake care of itself.\u201d\nSenator Nye devoted his efforts\nduring the afternoon largely to ob\ntaining information concerning one\n\u201cR. F. Bash\u201d who was subpoenaed\nby the committee Friday at Fargo.\nHe was served, but failed to appear,\nalthough he was registered at a\nFargo hotel.\n\u201cIn all probability this 'R. F..\nBash,\u2019 whom the committee con-|\nsiders a very important witness, is\nthe R. F. Bashford, the Dannenberg\ndetective agency has testified was in\nits employ and sent to Fargo with\nC. Clark Albers to shadow the com- j\nmittee after its retyn from Glacier\nnational park,\u201d Senator Nye said.\n\nA Surprise Witness\nThe surprise witness was Lloyd E.\nBemis, Chicago accountant, em\nployed by the committee.\nBemis testified one of Mrs. Mc\n(Continued on Page Eight'\n138-Mile An Hour Wind Tears Roofs\nFrom Houses in Santo Domingo; Cuba\nAnd Florida Fear Strike of Cyclone\n<By the Associated Press)\nCuba, Florida, and the gulf coast\nlooked with uneasiness toward the\nsoutheast tonight as an ominous\nsilence followed unconfirmed re\nports of devastation in Santo Do\nmingo by a tropical hurricance.\nCommunication with the city\ni ceased shortly after 3:30 p. m\u201e i\nFirst Picture Of Sinking Tahiti Off Which 317 Were Rescued\nW I JE\nI K\nt K fr\n\nHere are first pictures of the sinking of the passenger liner Tahiti, Aug. 17, south of Rarctonga, in the\nSouth Seas. Pictures were taken by survivors after they had abandoned the San Francisco-Australian\nliner. Photo above rhews the vessel beginning to settle, and a lifeboat putting off. Inset, a graphic last\nview of the Tahiti, going down to the bottom in a cloud of smoke, steam and water, with part of one\nmast showing. Pictures rushed to NEA Service for The Dcuglas Daily Dispatch by the Matron Liner Ven\ntura, rescuer of the survivors.\nxfWSfe\n*yJWMWWJ* Jk\" -^lg tiSl^^\n..^ll^j\u00df|p|ii|i|l|lip^^\n^fjgfr'Jr\njk yWw co l\nft :ffiiljj\u00a7|jgLj-Ss\u00a7sijS\u00df\u00df3^^JjMwffiw\u00df3ap'lff^\n\nThis graphic first picture from the sinking of the San Francisco-Australian liner Tahiti, looks down\nfrom the deck of the doomed vessel into a lifeboat just about to leave the ship. The photog-apher also\nhad tc flee the vessel, and carry his films to Honolulu, whence they were carried by the rescue vessel,\nthe Matson liner Ventura, to San Francisco for NE A Service and The Douglas Daily Dispatch.\n400,000 Soldiers\nTo Launch Drive\nIn China Friday\nAttempt to Hurl Rebels\nOut of Path Will Be\nMade By Nationalists\nSHANGHAI, Sept. 3 (47\u2014Nation\nalist armies flung themselves\nagainst rebel forces in Honan and\nShantung provinces today, renewing\nthe struggle for control of China\u2019s\ngovernment. Tientsin, stronghold\nof the northern alliance war lords,\nwas the objective.\nTelegraphing from his field head\nquarters in northern Kiangsi. Presi\ndent Chiang Kai-Shek said his\ntroops who drove the northerners\nout of Tsinan, Shantung capital,\nAug. 15, had clashed with insurgents\nnorth of the Yellow river. The drive\ntoward Tientsin, chief port of north\nChina, would be begun soon, Chiang\nsaid.\nSharp fighting in Honan, with the\nrebels pushed back slightly, was re\nported by Chiang. A great drive by\n400.0C0 nationalists would start Fri\nday, he said, to hurl rebels led by\nGen. Feng Yu-Hsiang out of the\nprovince where they have been eq\ntrenched since May.\neastern standard time, when a re\nport was received in Porto Rico\nthat a wind of 150 miles or more\nwas lifting the roofs from houses\nand all communications and power\nlines were rapidly going down.\nAbout this time communication by\nway of all-America cables ceased.\n(Continued on Page Eight)\nBalzar Certain\nOf Nomination\nIn Governor Race\nRENO, Nev., Sept. 3 (47\u2014Vir\ntually complete returns tonight on\nyesterday\u2019s primary assured Gov\nernor Fred B. Balzar of the re\npublican' gubernatorial nomination\nby a two to one margin over his\nnearest opponent, Mayor E. E.\nRoberts, of Reno.\nOn returns from 95 per cent of\nthe state, the governor was leading\nby more than 4000 votes.\nTabulations made by the' Reno\nEvening Gazette at 2 p. m., with\nabout one thousand scattered votes\nin the state missing, gave for re\npublican nomination for governor:\nBalzar, 7934; Roberts. 3823: Cowles,\n1835.\nFor democratic nomination for\ngovernor: Richards, 4699; Agee,\n4112.\nWill of Publisher Who Disappeared\nAt Sea Admitted to Probate; Estates\nOf Three Million Dollars Involved\n\u2014II W\nI Peace Move Failing\nIn India loHowing j\nGandhi Conferences!\n\u2022i\u2014\u2022\nPOONA, India, Sept. 3 \u2014A\nfeeling that the last move toward\npeace in India had been made and\nthe conferences of the two mod\nerates, Sir Tej Bahadur and Mr.\nJayakar, with the Mahatma Gand\nhi and his followers in civil dis\nobedience, would fail of their ob\njectives, pervaded this prison city\ntonight.\nBelief Expressed\nSenator Joyce Was\nVictim of Poison\nWidow Asserts She Will\nContinue Investigation\nof Death\nCHICAGO. Sept. 3 <47\u2014Discovery\nof a deady poison in the organs\nof State Senator John T. Joyce\ndeepened the mystery today of his\ndeath by murder or suicide on the\nmorning of August 16.\nA coroner's jury, informed of the\nchemist\u2019s findings, returned a ver\ndict that left the agency of death\nundetermined.\nThe senator\u2019s widow was aroused\nby an opinion of the state's attor\nney that Joyce was not slain, and\nasserted she would continue her in\nvestigation and prove her husband\nwas put to death by enemies.\n(Continued on sage Eighi)\nBALTIMORE. Sept. 3 Van\nLear Black, publisher, capitalist and\nworld flier, who disappeared into\nthe night from his yacht on Au\ngust 18. was legally adjudged to be\ndead today after hearing, and his\nwill, disposing of an estate of more\nI than $3,000,000. was admitted to\nprobate.\nThe presence in court of an at\ntorney for Van Lear Black, Jr., the\neldest sen. and two minor children\nof the publisher, who asked for a\ndelay in recognizing the instrument,\nindicated the possibility an attempt\nto break the will might be made,\n1 but none would discuss this.\nCaptain John N. Kelly, of the\ni (Continued on Page Eight)\nMetal Market\nCopper quiet; electrolytic, spot and\nfuture 10^4-11. Iron quiet; un\nchanged. Tin quiet; spot and near\nby 29.75; future 30.00. Lead steady;\nspot N. Y. 5.50; East St. Louis 535.\nZinc steady; East St. Louis spot and\nfuture 4.30-4.35. Antimony 7.75-\n7.87. Bar silver, 35VkC.\nNumber 57\nPolitical\nExcitement\nRuns High\nPolice Quell Threatening\nRiot When Students\nSwarm Out of Classes\nCabinet Members Hold\nMany Secret Meetings\nDissension in Regime of\nLeader Reported in Po\nlitical Cirdes\nBUENOS AIRES, Sept. 3. oP>\u2014\nRumors President Yrigoyen had\nbeen asked by leaders of his own.\nparty to resign, and had refused\nwere published today by the news\npaper La Critica, and served to in\ntensify the excitement in political\ncircles.\nMeanwhile, members of the cabi\nnet continued meeting behind closed\ndoers, and radical party leaders held\na secret conference. The public\nhourly expected announcements of\nmajor importance, and the silence\nmaintained by the chiefs whetted\ntheir curiosity and increased their\nworries.\nr Regarding the request that W\ngoyen resign, La Critica said it had\nthe information from most re-\nliable source.\u201d The paper named\nDr. Osvaldo Meabe, Yrigoyen\u2019s priv\nate physician, as the man who car-\n|ried to the president the request of\ni his erstwhile adherents.\n(Continued on Page Eight*\nMcGraw Is Signed\nTo Manage Giants\nFor Next 5 Years\nVeteran Pilot Given New\nContract, Spiking Ru\nmors He Was Leaving\nNEW YORK, Sept. 3 (47\u2014John\nJ. McGraw, for 28 years manager\nof the New York Giants, today\nsigned a contract to manage the\nNational league club for the next\nfive years.\nIn making the announcement of\nMcGraw\u2019s signing another long\nterm contract, Charles A. Stone\nham, president of the Giants, said\nit had been the club\u2019s plan to have\nthe formal signing at the expira\ntion of th\u00ae present contract, but\nrumors of McGraw\u2019s leaving the\nGiants and the National league\nprompted immediate action. Man\nager McGraw\u2019s present contract\nexpires at the close of this year.\nManager McGraw himself hand\ned a statement from President\nStoneham to newspaper men at the\ndowntown offices of the Giant*\nthis afternoon.\n\u201cMr. Stoneham and I .reached\nan agreement six months ago,\u201d he\nsaid, \u201cand another contract would\nhave been signed about the begin\nning of the new .year, but with\nthese foolish stories gA^g around\nthat I would manage another club,\nor even leave the National for the\nAmerican league, caused us to con\nclude the business now.\u201d\nI Four Shot During\nGun Fight Between\nPosse And Bandits\nTOLSTOY, 8. D., Sept. 3 (T>--\nTwo bandits were shot and wound\ned. a third was captured, and two\npossemen were shot and wounded\nin a gun fight near here today.\nThe bandits had held up the\nFirst State bank of Hoven, nine\nmiles west of here, this afternoon.\nA posse pursued them and the\nrobbers were surrounded in the\nbasement of a house. The gun\nfight followed.","height":"26277","width":"20277"}}
